# FEA Results

## Objective
Finite Element Analysis was carried out on the output spur gear to evaluate tooth-root bending stress and displacement under representative torque loading.

---

## Stress Results
The maximum von Mises stress occurred at the loaded tooth root fillet, which is the expected critical region for bending stress in a spur gear. This confirms that the simulation setup produced physically realistic results.

Peak stress remained well below the assumed material yield strength, indicating that the selected gear dimensions are appropriate for the intended loading condition.

---

## Displacement Results
Maximum displacement occurred near the loaded tooth tip, while the bore region remained effectively constrained. This is consistent with expected cantilever-like bending behaviour of a loaded gear tooth.

The displacement magnitude was very small, indicating that gear deformation would have minimal impact on meshing performance under the analysed load case.

---

## Engineering Interpretation
The results support the structural feasibility of the gearbox design for concept-level robotic drivetrain use. Both the stress distribution and displacement pattern align with expected mechanical behaviour, and no abnormal deformation or unrealistic stress concentrations were observed.

---

## Conclusion
The FEA study provided confidence that the selected gear geometry is suitable for the intended gearbox application. At this design stage, the gear can be considered structurally acceptable for preliminary robotic actuation use, subject to further refinement and testing if developed into a physical prototype.
